standard move order.} ({If Black starts with} 4... Nbd7 {you can consider
playing} 5. f4 ({The thing is that the usual} 5. Nf3 {would provide Black with
the additional option of} d5 6. Qe2) 5... Be7 6. Ne2 {White powerful centre
gives him excellent attacking possibilities.}) 5. Nf3 Nbd7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6
{Black is playing the style of Philidor without realizing that the position is
completely different now. Since White does not have a knight on c3, the move ..
.c7-c6 is not connected to ...b7-b5. Whenever Black plays ...b7-b5, White will
undermine the queenside by means of a2-a4.} ({In my opinion, more to the point
would be} 7... Re8 8. Nbd2 Bf8 9. Nf1 {We can easily see that White is playing
Ruy Lopez with a few extra tempi.} g6 10. Bg5 {This is one of the many
possible options in this position. The idea is to provoke the weakening ...
h7-h6. Otherwise, White will follow with Qd2 and Ng3 with nice attacking
chances on the kingside.} h6 11. Bh4 ({As we are going to witness in the next
model games, the move} 11. Bd2 {is perfectly playable as well.}) 11... Bg7 12.
N1d2 $1 {Suddenly, White switches to a favourable version of the Torre. Black
has no counterplay in this position. White usually keeps a solid advantage by
making natural moves.} b6 13. Qc2 Bb7 14. Rad1 Kh7 15. Bf1 {For the time being,
White keeps the tension. Under favourable circumstances, he is more than ready
to play dxe5 followed by Nc4. In such positions, Black does not have the
option of winning queenside space. The following cooperative line} a5 16. Bb5
c6 17. Bf1 b5 18. a4 {It becomes clear that Black cannot keep his queenside
structure intact.}) ({The thematic reaction to} 7... c5 {would be} 8. dxe5 Nxe5
9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Qc2 {White has a classical advantage due to the weak
d5-square. A possible idea is to exchange the light-squared bishops as well as
the f6-knight (for the dark-squared bishop). Afterwards, White can establish a
knight on d5.}) 8. Nbd2 Re8 ({As usual, the move} 8... b5 {will be countered by
} 9. a4 $1 {when Black cannot keep his queenside intact.} Qb6 10. axb5 cxb5 11.
Nf1 {White's central domination allows him to play on both wings.}) 9. Nf1 ({
Another thematic idea would be} 9. Bc2 {sidestepping any ...d6-d5 ideas and
preparing Bb3 under favourable circumstances.}) ({The setup} 9. b3 $6 Bf8 10.
Bb2 Qc7 11. Qc2 g6 12. c4 {is possible but I don't prefer it too much.}) 9...
Bf8 10. Ng3 {A typical Ruy Lopez style of play.} ({The alternative is} 10. Bg5
{In general, I prefer this move when Black has already committed to ...g7-g6.
Now, he can play} h6 $1 11. Bh4 Be7 $5 {[%cal Gf6h5] planning ...Nh5.} ({
As I have already pointed out, after} 11... g6 {White can get a favourable
version of Torre with} 12. N1d2 $16 Bg7 13. Bf1 Qc7 14. Nc4 exd4 15. Bg3 $16 {
with a huge advantage.}) 12. N1d2 Nh5 $14 {In this position, White is only
slightly better.}) 10... g6 ({Do not forget that} 10... b5 {will be answered
with} 11. a4 $16) 11. h3 {[%cal Gc1e3] This move indicates White's intention
of developing the bishop to e3.} ({the obvious alternative is} 11. Bg5 h6 ({
In case of} 11... Bg7 12. Qd2 {Black cannot challenge the annoying
construction Bg5 + Qd2.} Qc7 13. h3 b6 14. Rad1 Bb7 15. Bc2 {Once again, we
see this typical move. The bishop can easily occupy the b3-square.} {The
radical} c5 {runs into} 16. dxe5 dxe5 17. Qd6 $16 {with a huge advantage for
White.}) 12. Be3 Bg7 13. h3 d5 {It's important to remember that this advance
almost never equalises since White is ready for it. The thematic reaction
would be} 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Rxe5 16. f4 Re8 17. e5 $16 {with a huge
advantage.}) ({As always, it's possible to play} 11. Bc2) 11... Bg7 12. Be3 ({
Once again, playing} 12. Bg5 h6 13. Be3 Qc7 14. Qd2 {would have been a decent
possibility.}) 12... h6 13. Qd2 Kh7 14. Rad1 Qc7 15. Bb1 $5 {With this useful
move, White sidesteps the ideas based on ...d6-d5. Additionally, in a
favourable moment, she can play a2-a3 followed by Ba2.} ({More straightforward
would have been} 15. Nh4 $16 b5 16. f4 {with a strong attack.}) ({Another way
of preparing f2-f4 would have been} 15. Nh2 $1 $16 {Once again, the advance} d5
{does not manage to solve Black's problems.} (15... b6 16. f4 $16) 16. exd5
Nxd5 17. Nf3 $1 Nxe3 18. Qxe3 f5 19. dxe5 Nxe5 20. h4 {It's not clear how
Black will parry the threat of h4-h5.}) ({The option of} 15. Bc2 $16 {should
be kept in mind. In case of} c5 {White can even play} 16. b4 {trying to
clarify the situation in the centre.}) 15... b5 16. Nh2 Bb7 17. f4 c5 18. fxe5
dxe5 19. d5 $16 {White has a huge advantage. Besides the strong passed pawn,
there is a possibility to create play along the f-file.} Qd6 20. Rf1 Rac8 21.
b3 Nb6 22. Rf3 Rf8 23. Rdf1 Rc7 24. Rxf6 Bxf6 25. Bxh6 Rh8 26. Ng4 Bh4 27. Bg5
