-64,-20,-20,55,105,287,260,867,960,1219,1710,2101,29986] In the comments to
this game, I would like to briefly discuss a very important idea that you
should remember. Just pay attention to my comments to move 11.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4
Nf6 3. Bd3 e5 4. c3 Be7 5. Nf3 Nbd7 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. O-O b6 {This setup fails to
create any problems for White. We can just follow our scheme.} 8. Re1 Bb7 9.
Nf1 {Contrary to the Breyer Variation of Ruy Lopez ( with ...Re8 and ...Bf8
included), White now succeeds to transfer his knight to g3.} Re8 10. Ng3 Bf8
11. d5 {Even though this move is perfectly playable, I avoid closing the
centre in this way. The reason is that Black would get a KID of counterplay.} (
{My choice would have been} 11. h3 g6 ({After} 11... c5 {we should already play
} 12. d5 {getting a favourable version of King's Indian Defence. It's not
clear how Black can prepare the advance ...f7-f5.}) 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bd2 {
Due to the indirect pressure on e4, we should put the bishop on this square.} (
{After} 13. Be3 exd4 {White faces problems with the defence of the e4-pawn.}
14. cxd4 $2 ({Obviously,} 14. Bxd4 Bg7 $132 {is not what we want.}) 14... Nxe4
$19) 13... Bg7 14. Qc1 $3 {A fascinating idea that can be applied in many
openings. Before putting the queen to c2, it makes sense to provoke ...Kh7.}
Kh7 (14... h5 15. Bg5 $16) 15. Qc2 $3 $16 {White has a huge advantage. He can
increase the pressure by means of Nh4 followed by f2-f4. The opposition along
the diagonal b1-h7 is harmful to Black.}) 11... c6 12. c4 a6 13. Bd2 b5 14. b3
Nc5 15. Bf1 bxc4 16. bxc4 a5 17. Rb1 g6 18. Be3 Qc7 19. Nd2 a4 20. Bxc5 dxc5
21. Ne2 cxd5 22. cxd5 c4 23. Nc3 Ba6 24. Rc1 Bh6 25. Nxa4 Ng4 26. Rc2 Nxf2 27.
Kxf2 Qa7+ 28. Kf3 f5 29. Bxc4 fxe4+ 30. Nxe4 Rf8+ 31. Kg3 Bf4+ 32. Kh3 Bc8+ 33.
g4 Qxa4 34. Bb3 Qd7 35. d6+ Kh8 36. Rc7 Qd8 37. Qd5 h5 38. Re7 Bxg4+ 39. Kg2
Ra7 40. Qc5 Rd7 41. Rf1 Rf5 42. Rxf4 Qa8 43. Rxd7 Bf3+ 44. Rxf3 1-0

