Bxf3 {In such positions, White has a huge advantage due to his unopposed
light-squared bishop.} 13. Qxf3 g6 {This weakening move is more or less forced.
Otherwise, White will build a dangerous attack by means of Nf5.} 14. Bh6 ({
Another option would have been} 14. Bg5 Ne8 15. Bh6 Ne6 16. Bb3 {The b3-bishop
puts terrible pressure on Black's kingside.}) 14... Ne6 15. Rad1 {[%cal Gc2b3]
with Bb3 to follow. White's advantage is indisputable.}) 12. h3 {[%cal Gc1e3,
Gc2b3,Gd1c2,Ga1d1] This move always indicates White's intention of playing Be3.
Afterwards, it's possible to follow with Bb3 and Qc2.} b5 {As usual, gaining
queenside space is premature.} ({At the same time, the passive} 12... b6 13.
Bb3 h6 14. Be3 Bb7 15. Qc2 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gg3f5] gives White an obvious
advantage.} ({or} 15. Nf5)) 13. a4 $1 $16 {We should never forget this typical
reaction to ...b7-b5.} Rb8 14. Bd2 ({At this point, the simple} 14. axb5 $16 {
would have provided White with an obvious advantage.}) 14... a5 15. Qc1 Qb6 16.
Be3 Qc7 17. Qd1 b4 18. Bd3 Be6 19. c4 b3 20. d5 Bd7 21. Bd2 cxd5 22. cxd5 Rdc8
