76,120,122,140,159,165,165,155,144,135,139,139,136,116,71,70,-12,2,-118,-119,
-154,-170,-174,-152,-221,-243,-410,-110,-110,-160,-234,-234,-243,-243,-234,
-196,-285,-230,-281,-281,-281] In this game, we will start dealing with the
setups based on ...Nc6.} 1. d4 d6 2. e4 Nf6 3. Bd3 e5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 {
In my opinion, this is the most precise move. We keep the tension in the
centre until Black commits a concession.} ({In case of} 5. d5 Ne7 6. c4 g6 7.
Nc3 Bg7 {Black would get a normal KID position.}) 5... Bg4 {The most logical
move. By increasing the pressure, Black forces White to clarify the situation
in the centre.} ({After} 5... Be7 {we can already play} 6. d5 {since the
e7-square is no longer available for the knight.} Nb8 7. c4 {[%cal Gb1c3]
White gets a favourable version of the Old Indian Defence.}) 6. d5 {Now, when
the bishop has already occupied the g4-square, we can go for this structure.
In KID positions, Black's light-squared bishop is misplaced on g4.} Ne7 7. c4
g6 ({The alternative} 7... Ng6 {is well met by} 8. h3 Bd7 ({Playing without a
light-squared bishop is obviously not a wise decision. For instance, after} 
8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Be7 {White can further restrict Black's minor pieces by
means of} 10. g3 {[%cal Gh3h4] This is an important prophylactic against the
idea ...Nd7 followed by ...Bg5. At the same time, with his last move, White
restricts the g6-knight. A possible follow-up would be} Nd7 11. h4 Nc5 12. Bc2
a5 13. Nc3 {when White has a strategically winning position. He can actually
play on both wings.}) 9. Nc3 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gd1d2] White is planning to proceed
with Be3 followed by Qd2. Later on, he can even castle on the queenside.} {
The immediate} Nf4 {is well met by} 10. Bxf4 exf4 11. Qd2 Nh5 12. O-O-O {
with an overwhelming advantage for White.}) 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. h3 Bd7 10. Be3 ({
In this concrete position, the immediate} 10. c5 {is possible as well.}) 10...
O-O 11. g4 {Besides fighting against ...f7-f5, White also prevents ...Nh5.} ({
After} 11. O-O Nh5 {Black has enough counterplay.}) 11... h5 12. g5 {Even
though this move does not spoil anything, White could have played in a more
precise way.} ({In my opinion, the most continuation would have been} 12. Ng5
$1 c6 ({Taking the pawn allows White to build a decisive attack -} 12... hxg4
13. hxg4 Nxg4 14. Nh7 Nxe3 15. fxe3 Re8 16. Qf3 $18 f5 17. O-O-O {Black will
be soon checkmated.}) 13. Be2 hxg4 14. hxg4 cxd5 15. exd5 $16 {A typical
recapture. Besides opening the diagonal b1-h7, White makes the e4-square
available for his knights.} ({We should point out that the alternative} 15.
cxd5 {is playable as well. White can also play on the queenside as shown by
the following exemplary line -} b5 16. f3 b4 {The advance ...b7-b5-b4 makes
the c4-square available for the white knight.} 17. Nb1 a5 18. a4 ({But not} 18.
Nd2 {in view of} Nexd5 $1) 18... Rc8 19. Qb3 Qc7 20. Nd2 {White's advantage is
undisputable.})) 12... Ne8 13. Qe2 c6 14. O-O-O cxd5 15. cxd5 a6 16. Kb1 b5 17.
a3 Rc8 18. Rc1 Nc7 19. Bb6 Qe8 20. Nd2 Na8 21. Ba5 Rb8 22. Bb4 Nc8 23. Nb3 Qd8
24. Qe3 Nab6 25. Na5 Kh7 26. Nc6 Bxc6 27. dxc6 Qc7 28. Nd5 Nxd5 29. exd5 a5 30.
Bd2 b4 31. a4 Nb6 32. Qf3 Nxa4 33. Qxh5+ Kg8 34. Qg4 Nxb2 35. Be4 Na4 36. h4
