499,508,657,657,658,588,574,616,603,663,663,663,1186,1186] This is one of my
favourite games featuring the setup with early ...Nc6. GM Noel Studer executes
a very instructive positional idea.} 1. d4 d6 2. e4 Nf6 3. Bd3 e5 4. c3 Nc6 5.
Nf3 Bg4 6. d5 Ne7 7. h3 {Obviously, there is nothing wrong with this move
order.} ({White can also start with} 7. c4) 7... Bd7 8. c4 Ng6 9. Nc3 Be7 10.
O-O {In this specific case, White can afford castling. The thing is that with
a knight on g6, Black cannot easily prepare the advance ...f7-f5.} Nh5 {
[%cal Ge8g8,Gh5f4,Gf7f5] The only constructive idea. Black's next moves will
be ...Nhf4 followed by ...0-0 and ...f7-f5.} 11. Re1 {This is our thematic
reaction to ...Nh5. The idea is to answer} Nhf4 {with} 12. Bf1 O-O {Here comes
the most interesting moment. Black is ready to deliver ...f7-f5. White should
find a way to fight against the f4-knight.} 13. Kh2 $1 {This is an amazing
idea. By overprotecting the h3-pawn, Studer prepares the advance g2-g3.} Qc8
14. Ng1 {[%cal Gg2g3] Now, it turns out that there are no retreat square for
the knight. Therefore, Black played the passive} Nh8 ({The alternative} 14...
f5 {does not help in view of} 15. g3 fxe4 16. Nxe4 {when White is winning
anyway.}) 15. g3 Nfg6 16. h4 $16 {Black is completely busted. Later on, White
managed to covert his advantage.} Nxh4 (16... f5 17. h5 $18) 17. gxh4 Bxh4 18.
Be3 f5 19. Qh5 Ng6 20. Nf3 Bf6 21. Bh3 Ne7 22. Ng5 Bxg5 23. Bxg5 Ng6 24. Rg1 f4
25. f3 a6 26. a4 Rf7 27. Rg2 Bxh3 28. Qxh3 Qxh3+ 29. Kxh3 c6 30. Rd1 c5 31. a5
Rb8 32. Na4 Nf8 33. b4 cxb4 34. Rb1 h6 35. Bxh6 Nd7 36. Rxb4 Kh7 37. Bg5 Rh8
38. Bh4 Nf8 39. Kg4 Kg8 40. Bg5 Rh1 41. c5 Nh7 42. cxd6 Rd7 43. Nc5 Rxd6 44.
Rb6 Rxb6 45. axb6 Rb1 46. d6 Nf8 47. d7 Rd1 48. d8=Q 1-0

