{[%evp 0,65,19,31,75,63,83,37,20,10,35,6,8,14,61,8,25,-38,57,34,61,51,65,21,18,
13,35,26,33,20,24,1,11,17,19,-11,19,14,14,3,38,3,28,83,75,75,128,69,110,103,
110,119,105,120,149,246,246,249,250,512,529,284,512,224,205,201,219,219]} 1. e4
d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 e5 4. c3 Nbd7 5. f4 {This is the most principled reaction
to 4...Nbd7.} ({The lazy alternative is} 5. Nf3 d5 6. Qe2 {when White can
definitely fight for a small advantage. Note that not many players will play 5.
..d5. They game would rather transpose to the normal lines after 5...Be7.})
5... c5 {Black immediately strikes in the centre.} ({The usual continuation is
} 5... Be7 {when White should play} 6. Ne2 {The knight will occupy the
g3-square.} ({In case of} 6. fxe5 dxe5 7. d5 {Black would get access to the
important c5-square.}) ({The normal} 6. Nf3 {is very well met by} d5) 6... O-O
7. Ng3 {According to the computer, this is even more precise than the natural
7.0-0. Let's take a look at what might happen if Black keeps making natural
moves -} Re8 8. O-O Bf8 9. Qf3 c6 10. Be3 Qc7 11. fxe5 dxe5 12. Nd2 {White's
better development, powerful centre, and control of the f-file give him a huge
advantage.}) ({Nothing changes} 5... c6 6. Nf3 Qc7 7. O-O Be7 8. Kh1 O-O 9. Qe1
{with an indisputable advantage for White.}) 6. Nf3 {This is not the most
energetic reaction.} ({The computer indicates that after} 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Nf3
Bd6 8. Na3 {White is winning pretty much on the spot because Black cannot keep
his central control. The threat of Nc4 is really very annoying.}) 6... cxd4 ({
At this point, Black could have played} 6... d5 {with a total chaos.}) 7. cxd4
exd4 8. Nxd4 Nc5 9. Nc3 a6 10. O-O Be7 11. Nb3 $14 {This move is enough for a
small advantage.} ({Even more precise would have been the typical prophylactic
move} 11. Kh1 O-O 12. Be3 {Black's only counterplay is based on} d5 {It turns
out, however, that after} 13. e5 Nfe4 14. Qe2 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Nxd3 16. Qxd3 {
White's mobile centre gives him a big advantage.}) 11... Nxd3 12. Qxd3 O-O 13.
Be3 Be6 14. Nd4 Ng4 15. Rfe1 (15. Kh1 Nxe3 16. Qxe3 $14) 15... Rc8 16. Rad1 Qa5
17. Qd2 Qh5 18. h3 Nxe3 19. Qxe3 Rfe8 20. Kh2 Bf6 21. Nxe6 Rxe6 22. Nd5 h6 23.
Rd2 Rc4 24. Qd3 b5 25. b3 Rc5 26. Ree2 Rc1 27. Rc2 Rxc2 28. Rxc2 g5 29. Rc8+
Kg7 30. Nc7 Re7 31. Ne8+ Rxe8 32. Rxe8 gxf4 33. Qxd6 1-0

