{[%evp 0,41,24,9,64,64,64,36,36,19,19,-7,14,42,59,48,64,60,61,33,63,80,93,45,
109,108,69,93,131,183,187,75,71,81,81,71,241,229,231,230,589,700,700,572]} 1.
e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 e5 ({Note that Black can also start with} 3... Nbd7 {
In this case, the most ambitious approach would be} 4. f4 ({The other decent
option is} 4. Nf3 e5 5. c3 d5 6. Qe2 {with a small advantage.}) 4... e5 5. c3
Be7 6. Ne2 O-O 7. Ng3 {transposing to the main line.}) 4. c3 Nbd7 5. f4 c6 {
White is always better when Black goes for such passive setups.} 6. Nf3 Qc7 ({
Before playing Nf3 we should always calculate} 6... d5 {In this case, it does
not seem to work so well for Black because the move ...c7-c6 appears to be a
waste of time. Indeed, after} 7. Nxe5 Nxe4 8. O-O {[%cal Gb1d2] White has a
stable advantage.}) 7. O-O Be7 8. fxe5 dxe5 9. Bg5 O-O 10. Nbd2 {White got a
very favourable version of the Fantasy Variation in Caro-Kann Defence. He is
now planning to put pressure on the centre by means of Nc4.} Re8 11. Nc4 Ng4 {
Trying to force simplifications.} ({After} 11... exd4 12. e5 Nd5 13. e6 fxe6
14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Nfe5 $18 {[%cal Gd1h5] White is winning on the spot.}) 12.
h3 Bxg5 13. Nxg5 Nh6 14. Qh5 $18 Re7 (14... Nf6 15. Rxf6 $18) 15. a4 f6 16. Nf3
Nf7 17. Rad1 c5 18. Ne3 (18. d5 Nd6) 18... Qd8 19. Nf5 Re8 20. Bc4 Rf8 21. Nd6
(21. dxe5 fxe5 22. Ng5) 1-0

