29,13,116,94,55,144,-922,-1137] In the comments to this game, I will explain
how White should react against the setup based on ...h7-h6 followed by ...
g7-g5.} 1. d4 d6 2. e4 Nf6 3. Bd3 e5 4. c3 Be7 5. Nf3 Nbd7 6. O-O h6 {When we
see such a strange-looking move, we should keep our play as flexible as
possible. It's important to wait until our opponent shows his intentions.} 7.
h3 $6 {I don't like this move at all since sometimes the advance ...g7-g5-g4
might become dangerous.} ({More to the point would be} 7. Nbd2 $1 {when White
is more than well-prepared for} g5 ({If Black keeps making natural moves such
as} 7... O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nf1 Bf8 {Sooner or later, he will have to pay for
the premature ...h7-h6. A possible line would be} 10. Ng3 g6 11. h3 Bg7 12. Be3
c6 13. Qd2 Kh7 14. Rad1 $14 {when White's advantage is beyond question. The
classical way of developing the initiative would be Nh4 followed by f2-f4.}) 8.
Nc4 g4 9. Nh4 $1 {This is winning more or less by force.} ({The alternative} 9.
Nfd2 {is also enough for a huge advantage.}) 9... Nxe4 10. Ng6 fxg6 11. Bxe4 {
White is completely winning.}) 7... c6 8. Be3 Qc7 9. Nbd2 g5 10. Re1 Nf8 11.
