78,84,90,83,82,82,82,76,78,97,76,70,68,84,86,76,80,76,59,59,59,62,63,44,17,7,0,
0,0,3,0,0,0,0,0]} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 e5 4. dxe5 $5 {I call this line
"the end of chess". The reason is that if such a move is working, chess is not
logical at all. Surprisingly, it turns out that things are not so simple and
Black still faces some practical problems.} dxe5 5. Nf3 Nbd7 ({Probably, the
most precise reaction is} 5... Bc5 $1 6. c3 Nbd7 7. O-O O-O 8. Nbd2 {[%cal
Gd1c2,Gd2c4,Gb2b4,Ga2a4] Even now, however, the position remains playable.
After putting his knight on c4, White will start gaining space on the
queenside.}) ({The passive} 5... Bd6 {does not fully solve the problems -} 6.
Nbd2 $14 Nc6 7. c3 O-O 8. Nc4 (8. O-O) 8... Be6 9. Qe2 {White is slightly
better since the c6-knight is dominated by the c3-pawn. Later on, he can
consider gaining space on the queenside.}) 6. O-O Be7 $2 {As a matter of fact,
this natural move leads to a very difficult position for Black.} 7. Nbd2 c6 8.
b3 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gc1b2] White is ready to put pressure on e5 by means of Bb2
and Nc4.} ({The alternative would be} 8. Nc4 Qc7 9. b3 $16 ({Also possible is} 
9. a4 $16 O-O 10. b3 Re8 11. Bb2 Bf8 12. a5 {when Black is completely
paralyzed.}) 9... b5 10. Ne3 Nc5 11. Bb2 Nfd7 12. Nf5 Bf6 13. Re1 $16 {Once
again, White enjoys a huge advantage.}) 8... O-O ({In case of} 8... Nc5 {
White can play} 9. Bb2 (9. Nxe5 Qd4) 9... Nxd3 10. cxd3 Qxd3 11. Nxe5 Qd8 12.
Qe2 (12. Qc2 O-O 13. Rad1 $14) 12... O-O 13. Rad1 Qc7 14. f4 a5 15. f5 a4 16.
Nd3 $16 {The mobile centre gives White a huge advantage.}) 9. Bb2 Qc7 10. Nc4
$16 {Black is left without counterplay. Defending the e5-pawn is already very
difficult.} Bd6 11. Be2 Nxe4 12. Bd3 b5 13. Nxd6 Nxd6 14. Nxe5 Nc5 15. Qf3 f6
16. Qxc6 Qxc6 17. Nxc6 Nxd3 18. cxd3 Be6 19. Rfe1 Rfe8 20. Rac1 Nf5 21. f3 Kf7
