1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 c6 4. Bd3 d5 {Although this setup is very popular
for Black, with a correct play, White gets a very nice advantage.} {This is
one of my favourite structures that is always better for White when the black
bishop is on g7.} 5. exd5 ({Theoretically speaking, the move} 5. e5 {might be
even more precise.} {Note that we should always answer the move} Bg4 {with} 6.
Nbd2 {[%cal Gh2h3] preparing to recapture with a knight in case of ...Bxf3.
Since our knight is not on c3, Black cannot effectively attack the centre by
playing ...c6-c5. We are always ready to answer this advance with c2-c3.}) 5...
cxd5 6. c3 Nf6 ({Preventing Bf4 with} 6... Qc7 {does not solve Black's
problems. In this case, White can even play} 7. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5h4,Gh4g3]
planning to transfer the bishop to g3 via h4.}) 7. O-O O-O 8. h3 {When Black
has already committed to ...g7-g6, this move is not obligatory.} ({Probably, I
would have preferred} 8. Bf4 Nc6 9. Nbd2 {It's very important to understand
that the position arising after} Bf5 10. Bxf5 gxf5 {is terrible for Black. At
first sight, it might seem that Black has a fantastic position in view of ...
Ne4 followed by ...Kh8 and ...Rg8. In reality, things are far from simple.
Let's take a look at the following exemplary line -} 11. Ne1 $1 {[%cal Ge1d3]
A key move. The d3-square is the perfect spot for our knight in this pawn
structure.} Ne4 12. Nd3 e6 {White should now decide how to deal with the
e4-knight. There is a rule that is unfortunately not mentioned in the chess
literature. When we put pressure on a piece that we cannot capture, we only
make this piece stronger. The best strategy is to play around the piece and
completely ignore it. Hence, a logical follow-up would be} 13. Re1 Kh8 14. Nf1
$1 {[%cal Gf1g3,Gg3h5] White keeps ignoring the knight. The knight is heading
to the important h5-square. This is possible because Black has played ...gxf5.}
({Another option would be} 14. f3 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 {when White has a huge
advantage. Depending on the concrete circumstances, he will either open the
g-file by means of Kh1 followed by Rg1 and g2-g4, or open the h-file with
h2-h3 and g2-g4.})) 8... Nc6 9. Bf4 {In this position, Black is left without
counterplay. White's main advantage is his better bishops.} a6 10. a4 {
In general, I don't like this move. Black is actually not threatening to play.
..b7-b5.} ({More to the point would have been} 10. Nbd2 {We already know that
the structure arising after} Bf5 11. Bxf5 gxf5 {is terrible for Black.}) 10...
b6 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Qe2 Re8 13. Ne5 Nh5 14. Bh2 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Bh6 16. f4 Ng7
17. Nf3 Ne6 18. f5 Nc5 19. e6 g5 20. Ne5 fxe6 21. fxe6 Bg7 22. Nf7 Qc8 23.
Bxh7+ Kxh7 24. Qh5+ Kg8 25. Nxg5 1-0

