{[%evp 0,83,36,44,74,61,61,47,47,29,31,23,42,42,38,33,45,38,38,32,34,36,36,36,
36,36,42,45,66,26,54,53,53,24,16,-1,37,-7,-7,2,216,220,283,283,283,243,299,299,
272,199,202,202,239,239,300,162,564,296,297,352,362,362,355,302,368,376,376,
341,350,326,431,437,450,436,450,450,453,463,490,458,551,551,654,654,662,662]
In the following blitz game, I have illustrated how White should fight against
the seemingly strong e4-knight.  We have reached the same structure via the
Caro-Kann move order.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 g6 6.
Nf3 Bg7 7. O-O Nf6 8. Bf4 O-O 9. Nbd2 {You can see that I don't rush with the
move Re1. The reason is that in many cases we should keep the e1-square
available for the knight. That's what happened in the game.} Bf5 10. Bxf5 gxf5
11. Ne1 $1 {[%cal Ge1d3] Never forget this typical idea.} e6 12. Nd3 Ne4 13.
Re1 {[%cal Gd2f1] As you already know, White should play around the black
knight. The next move is going to be Nf1.} Qf6 14. Nf1 Qg6 {Even though the
queen controls the important h5-square, it's obviously misplaced on g6.} 15. f3
Nf6 {[%csl Rg6]} 16. h3 {The idea of this move is to eventually follow with
g2-g4 at some point. Obviously, the quality of the moves is not optimal
because this is a blitz game! In any case, Black is already significantly
worse.} Nh5 17. Bd2 Bh6 18. g4 fxg4 19. hxg4 f5 $2 {This move is actually
dropping a piece. Afterwards, I managed to effortlessly convert the advantage.}
20. Bxh6 Qxh6 21. gxh5 $18 Qxh5 22. Kf2 Qh4+ 23. Ke2 Rae8 24. Ne5 Nxe5 25. dxe5
Rf7 26. Qd4 Qh3 27. Ne3 Rg7 28. Qf4 Ree7 29. Rh1 Qg3 30. Qxg3 Rxg3 31. Rag1 f4
32. Rxg3+ fxg3 33. Rh3 Rg7 34. Ng4 h5 35. Rxh5 g2 36. Kf2 Kf7 37. Kxg2 Ke7 38.
Kg3 b5 39. Kf4 b4 40. cxb4 d4 41. Ke4 d3 42. Kxd3 1-0

