{[%evp 0,81,36,30,78,78,74,38,86,36,54,56,53,53,50,39,44,23,43,43,64,54,50,10,
32,6,52,60,34,-24,66,66,68,57,57,47,27,17,17,17,3,0,0,8,6,20,20,26,27,27,21,29,
36,32,99,175,137,137,145,154,156,46,227,245,245,245,266,227,262,261,267,257,
312,254,485,396,871,444,935,1198,1209,1228,1228,1196] This game is a very good
illustration of how to fight against the setups based on ...e7-e5 and ...Ne7.} 
1. d4 g6 2. e4 Bg7 3. Nf3 d6 4. c3 Nd7 5. Bd3 e5 6. O-O Ne7 {As we are going
to witness a bit later, the black knight is actually misplaced on e7. We
should only refrain from closing the centre with d4-d5 because Black is
perfectly ready for that.} ({As we are going to see in the section dedicated
to the Pirc setups, the move} 6... Ngf6 {can be met by} 7. Bg5 {when White
gets a very favourable version of the Torre.}) 7. Na3 $1 {This is a very
subtle idea. Since the e7-knight does not put pressure on the centre, we can
put our knight on the perfect c4-square.} ({A more precise way of executing
the same idea would have been} 7. Re1 $3 O-O 8. a4 $3 $16 {[%cal Gb1a3,Ga3c4]
Only now White will proceed with Na3-c4. The reason is that Black cannot chase
the knight away with ...a7-a6 followed by ...b7-b5.} a6 ({When there is
tension in the centre, Black cannot go for a flank attack with} 8... f5 $4 {
After} 9. Ng5 $18 {he can already resign.}) ({Note that after} 8... a5 9. Na3
b6 10. Nc4 {Black does not have favourable way of challenging the c4-knight.
The c4-knight became a stronghold. White should only find the favourable
moment for dxe5.} Bb7 11. dxe5 (11. Bg5) 11... dxe5 12. Be3 {[%cal Gd1c2,Ga1d1]
followed by Qc2 and Rad1. The superior activity of the white pieces yields him
an advantage. Just look at the e7-knight!}) 9. a5 $1 {When you see the move ...
a7-a6, you should immediately fix the structure.} c6 ({Better is} 9... Nc6 {
when White can play} 10. Bc4 ({or} 10. Bg5)) 10. Nbd2 $16 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gd4e5,
Gd6e5] White is strategically winning. Black is completely paralyzed.}) 7...
O-O 8. Re1 exd4 {This move gives White a stable advantage.} ({The most
challenging would have been} 8... a6 9. Nc4 b5 $132 {That's why I always
prefer to include a2-a4 before bringing the knight to c4.}) 9. cxd4 d5 10. e5
c5 11. Nc2 $16 {After an intense fight, Sargissian managed to convert his huge
advantage.} Nc6 12. Bg5 Qa5 13. b4 cxb4 14. Rb1 Nb6 15. Nxb4 Nc4 16. Nxc6 bxc6
17. Nd2 Be6 18. Re2 Rfb8 19. Nb3 Qa3 20. Bc1 Qe7 21. Nc5 Rxb1 22. Bxb1 Rb8 23.
Bd3 Rb5 24. Nxe6 Qxe6 25. h3 h5 26. f4 c5 27. Bxc4 dxc4 28. d5 Qf5 29. d6 Rb8
30. Rc2 g5 31. Rxc4 gxf4 32. Rxc5 Rd8 33. Qd5 Kh7 34. Kh2 Re8 35. Bb2 h4 36.
Rc4 Bxe5 37. d7 f3+ 38. Qxe5 Rxe5 39. d8=Q f2 40. Rxh4+ Kg6 41. Rg4+ 1-0

