766,787,805,805,815,815,28702,1322,1322,29976,29977,29978,29993,29990,29991,
29992,29993,29994,29995,29996,29997,29998,29999,-30000]} 1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3.
Nf3 d6 4. c3 a6 {As we are going to see in a while, this move order is not
effective against the setups with c2-c3. The problem is that whenever Black
plays ...b7-b5, White will be ready to answer with a2-a4.} ({Another way of
playing the Modern Defence would be} 4... Nd7 5. Bd3 b6 6. O-O Bb7 7. a4 ({
Another typical idea is} 7. Re1 e5 8. Bg5 {This move is very annoying. If
Black plays 8...Nf6, then White gets a favourable version of the Torre with 9.
Nbd2.} Ne7 9. a4 $1 {[%cal Gb1a3,Ga3c4] In the previous example, we have seen
that against the setups with ...Ne7, White should play a2-a4 followed by the
maneuver Na3-c4.} a6 10. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c4] with Nc4 to follow. White has an
obvious advantage.}) 7... a5 {As we all know by now, when Black has committed
to ...a7-a5, the c4-square becomes a stronghold for our knight.} 8. Na3 {
[%cal Ga3c4]}) 5. Bd3 Nf6 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 Nfd7 {This is an attempt to
prepare ...e7-e5. White follows with the natural} 8. Bg5 {when it's not clear
how Black can make use of his last move.} h6 9. Bh4 b5 (9... b6 10. Nbd2 Bb7
11. Qe2 $16) 10. a4 $1 {This is always our thematic reaction to ...b7-b5.
Black cannot keep his queenside intact.} bxa4 11. Rxa4 Bb7 (11... Nb6 12. Ra1
$16) 12. Nbd2 c5 13. Nc4 ({In positions with a pawn on e7 and bishop on b7,
more precise would be} 13. d5 $1 Nb6 14. Ra1 N8d7 15. Bg3 $16 {with a huge
advantage for White. Black does not have any counterplay.}) 13... cxd4 14. cxd4
g5 15. Bg3 Nc6 16. d5 Na7 17. Na5 Nc5 18. Nxb7 Nxb7 19. Rxa6 Nc5 20. Ra2 Qb6
21. Bb1 Nb5 22. Rxa8 Rxa8 23. e5 Qa5 24. h3 Qb4 25. Qe2 Nd4 26. Nxd4 Qxd4 27.
