1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 ({At this point, I would like to mention that if Black
wants to play the Norvegian Rat with} 2... Nf6 {we can follow the same setup
with} 3. Bd3) 3. Nf3 d6 4. c3 b6 5. Bb5+ $5 {When Black opts for the early ...
b7-b6, you should always have this check in mind. Black is now forced to spoil
his own coordination.} ({After the usual} 5. Bd3 Bb7 6. O-O e6 7. Nbd2 Nd7 8.
Re1 Ne7 {we reach the so-called Hipopotamus Opening which will be discussed a
bit later.}) 5... Bd7 {This move is an obvious concession. The bishop belongs
to b7.} ({In case of} 5... c6 6. Bd3 d5 7. exd5 cxd5 8. O-O Nf6 9. Bf4 {
We have reached our familiar structure from the Caro-Kann Exchange with a
bishop on g7. Obviously, the inclusion of the move ...b7-b6 is not in Black's
favour.}) ({After a move such as} 5... Nd7 {Black should always reckon with
the possibility of} 6. Bc6) 6. Bd3 {After forcing the bishop to the
unfavourable d7-square, we can retreat.} ({The move} 6. a4 {is possible as
well.}) 6... c5 7. O-O ({When Black has a pawn on e7, instead of e5, the most
principled reaction is} 7. d5 $1) 7... Nc6 8. d5 Ne5 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. f4 $16 {
White got a huge advantage and later on managed to convert it in a full point.}
Qc7 11. Na3 exf4 12. Bxf4 Be5 13. Bxe5 Qxe5 14. Nc4 Qg5 15. e5 Nh6 16. e6 fxe6
17. dxe6 Bxe6 18. Be4 Rd8 19. Bc6+ Bd7 20. Qa4 Qd5 21. Bxd7+ Rxd7 22. Rad1 Qb7
23. Ne5 b5 24. Rxd7 Qxd7 25. Qa6 Qc7 26. Qxb5+ Kd8 27. Rd1+ Kc8 28. Qa6+ 1-0

