{This game is a very good illustration of how to play against the so-called
Hipopotamus Variation.} 1. d4 g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 3. c3 d6 4. e4 b6 5. Bd3 ({
Obviously, White could have started with} 5. Bb5+ {that was dealt with in the
previous game.}) 5... Bb7 6. O-O Nd7 7. Re1 h6 {By taking the control of the
g5-square, Black is planning to continue with ...e7-e6 followed by ...Ne7.} ({
In my opinion, the most practical response to} 7... e5 {is} 8. Bg5 {when most
likely we will get a Torre type of position.} ({With the bishop being already
committed to b7, it makes some sense to play} 8. d5 {Nevertheless, I am not a
big fan of this move.})) 8. Nbd2 {Obviously, Kamsky didn't know the exact theory
in this position. Actually, he does not need it since in this setup he can
easily play on general grounds.} e6 9. Nf1 Ne7 10. Ng3 c5 {This break fits
into the philosophy of the variation. After giving the centre away, Black
starts attacking it with pawn breaks.} 11. Be3 Qc7 12. a4 {As you have already
seen by now, I am not a big fan of this advance. Instead, I would have
preferred a move such as 12.Qd2.} O-O 13. Qd2 $1 {This is an important move in
White's setup. The idea is to provoke ...Kh7. The king is usually poorly
placed against the light-squared bishop.} Kh7 14. h4 $1 {Another thematic idea.
White is now ready to further weaken Black's kingside by means of h4-h5.} e5
15. h5 Nf6 16. Qe2 Bc8 17. dxe5 {Played in accordance with the variation.
Additionally, Kamsky is a big fan of the static positions.} dxe5 18. Nh2 Be6
19. Bc4 {Preventing the positional threat of ...c5-c4 and proposing a
favourable exchange of the light-squared bishops.} ({In case of} 19. Nhf1 c4
$132 {Black's queenside space gives him enough counterplay.}) 19... Qc8 20. Ba6
Qc7 21. Bc4 Bxc4 22. hxg6+ fxg6 23. Qxc4 {White has a slight but stable
advantage. After an interesting fight, Kamsky won the game.} Ne8 24. Rad1 Qc6
25. Nf3 Nc7 26. Rd2 Rad8 27. Red1 Rxd2 28. Rxd2 Nc8 29. Qd3 Qxa4 30. Qd7 Qxd7
31. Rxd7 Ne6 32. Nxe5 Rd8 33. Rb7 Re8 34. Nc6 Nd6 35. Rxa7 Nc4 36. Bc1 Rc8 37.
Ne7 Rd8 38. Nd5 Kh8 39. Ne2 Nd6 40. f3 g5 41. Nxb6 Rb8 42. Nd5 Nc4 43. Ra2 Ne5
44. f4 gxf4 45. Bxf4 Rb7 46. Bxe5 Bxe5 47. Ra6 Ng5 48. Rxh6+ Kg7 49. Rh5 Nf7
50. b4 c4 51. Ne3 Kg6 52. Rf5 1-0

