{In this example, we will see how White should react against the quick ...
e7-e5.} 1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 d6 ({Let me remind you that after} 3... c6 4.
Bd3 d6 5. O-O e5 6. c3 Ne7 {White should already prepare the manoeuvre
Nb1-a3-c4 (the black knight is on e7!). The best way to achieve it is} 7. dxe5
dxe5 8. a4 O-O 9. Na3 {with a pleasant advantage.}) 4. c3 e5 5. Bg5 {This is
the simplest solution. Once again, White is heading for a Torre type of play.}
({When we have played c2-c3 instead of Nc3, the option} 5. dxe5 dxe5 6. Qxd8+
Kxd8 7. Bc4 {is completely playable.}) 5... f6 6. Be3 Nh6 7. Bc4 Nf7 8. Bxf7+
Kxf7 9. Qb3+ Ke8 10. O-O c6 11. Nbd2 {By playing an only natural move, White got
a nice advantage. This is what usually happens when our opponent tries to
avoid the theory at any cost.} Qe7 12. Rad1 Be6 13. c4 Na6 14. d5 1-0

