{[%evp 0,71,19,31,75,63,83,37,20,14,79,51,45,41,54,40,63,32,57,35,42,-16,7,12,
17,-9,9,0,-8,16,28,34,26,12,12,29,35,7,27,27,45,33,31,19,50,-33,-26,-199,-1,53,
65,0,0,0,-6,-16,-3,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,7,-21,52,-91,17,17,17,-43,10,15]} 1. e4 d6 2.
d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 e5 4. c3 g6 5. Nf3 Nc6 {This is one of the most ambitious setups.
Black is trying to put maximum pressure to the centre.} 6. h3 {Usually, this
move is connected with the intention of developing the bishop to e3. In this
case, Black wouldn't have the option of ...Ng4.} ({Personally, I would have
played} 6. O-O Bg7 7. dxe5 {We can play this move as soon as Black puts his
bishop on g7.} ({The Torre approach does not work quite well in this position.
For example, after} 7. Re1 O-O 8. Bg5 {Black can play} exd4 9. cxd4 h6 10. Bh4
g5 11. Bg3 Nh5 {putting a lot of pressure on White's centre.}) 7... Nxe5 {
This is almost always the right recapture.} ({After} 7... dxe5 {the c6-knight
will be a liability. White can already opt for a Torre type of play by means of
} 8. Bg5 O-O 9. Qc2 {In this structure, the queen must go to c2!} ({The
natural-looking} 9. Qe2 {is an inaccuracy. For example, after} h6 10. Bh4 Qe8
11. Nbd2 Nh5 {the white queen is misplaced in view of the threat of ...Nf4.})
9... Bg4 10. Nbd2 h6 11. Bh4 Qe7 12. Rfe1 Rad8 13. Be2 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gb2b4,
Ga2a4,Gc4e3] An important move. White is preparing Nc4 followed by pawn
expansion on the queenside.} Rfe8 14. Nc4 a6 15. Ne3 Be6 16. b4 {White has an
obvious advantage. We can now see, how useless is the c6-knight.}) 8. Nxe5 dxe5
9. a4 {[%cal Gb1a3] White already prepares the manoeuvre Nb1-a3-c4.} O-O 10. Na3
Be6 11. Bg5 Qe7 12. Qc2 h6 13. Bh4 Rfd8 ({A typical positional mistake would be
} 13... g5 14. Bg3 Nh5 15. Bc4 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Ga3c4,Gc4e3,Ge3f5] After the
thematic exchange of the light-squared bishops, White can transfer his knight
towards the week f5-square.}) 14. Bc4 Bxc4 15. Nxc4 c6 16. b4 {[%cal Gf2f3,
Gh4f2] Once again, White gets his classical Torre slight advantage. He is
ready to proceed with f2-f3 followed by Bf2.}) 6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 ({
In my opinion, better would have been} 8. Be3 Re8 9. Nbd2 h6 10. Re1 {when
it's not obvious how Black will create counterplay.}) 8... a5 9. Bg5 $6 {
In my opinion, this is a slightly dubious decision. The move Bg5 is not well
combined with h2-h3.} h6 10. Bh4 exd4 11. Nxd4 {If White is forced to
recapture with the knight, something has gone wrong with his strategy.} ({
The problem is that after} 11. cxd4 g5 12. Bg3 Nh5 $132 {Black has more than
enough counterplay.} ({or} 12... g4 13. hxg4 Bxg4 $132)) 11... Ne5 12. Bf1 g5
13. Bg3 Re8 14. Nd2 Ng6 15. a4 Bd7 16. Bc4 Ne5 17. Bb3 Nd3 18. Re3 Nc5 19. Bc2
Bc6 20. Qe2 Qd7 21. Nf5 Bf8 22. f4 Nfxe4 23. Nxe4 Nxe4 24. Bxe4 Rxe4 25. Rxe4
Qxf5 26. Re3 gxf4 27. Rf1 f3 28. Rfxf3 Bxf3 29. Rxf3 Qe6 30. Re3 Qf5 31. Re4
Bg7 32. Rg4 Kh7 33. Kh2 Rg8 34. Rf4 Qe6 35. Qd3+ Qg6 36. Qf3 1/2-1/2

