{[%evp 0,51,34,23,27,34,44,40,36,16,53,44,73,52,80,49,46,49,57,43,96,38,59,4,
39,18,69,48,64,54,102,94,97,94,100,93,118,107,115,386,389,403,407,413,418,420,
459,469,478,458,493,492,499,502]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 {This time, our thematic
structure will be reached via Torre move order. Actually, this does not matter
at all since the type of position remains unchanged.} 3. Bg5 Bg7 4. Nbd2 d6 5.
e4 a6 {When Black plays anti-theoretical moves in these setup, White gets a
nice advantage with natural moves.} ({A more classical continuation would be} 
5... O-O 6. c3 Nc6 7. Bd3 e5 8. dxe5 Nxe5 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Qc2 {when we reach
the classical Torre position.}) 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. O-O O-O 8. c3 Rb8 $6 {Finding
himself in an unfamiliar position, Black starts making unusual moves. Hence,
White gets a huge advantage with standard play.} ({More to the point would
have been} 8... e5 {when White should play} 9. dxe5 ({In positions with ...Nc6,
keeping the central tension is hardly a good idea. For instance, after} 9. Re1
h6 10. Bh4 exd4 11. cxd4 g5 12. Bg3 Nh5 {White cannot easily hold his centre
intact. After} 13. d5 Nxg3 14. hxg3 Ne5 {Black's bishop pair and domination on
the dark squares gives him excellent play.}) 9... dxe5 10. Qc2 {[%cal Gd2c4,
Gb2b4,Ga2a4] with a fantastic position in view of the misplaced c6-knight.}) ({
The move} 8... Bg4 {is never a problem. White can simply play} 9. h3 Bxf3 10.
Nxf3 e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Qc2 {with a classical advantage. For
instance, after} h6 14. Be3 Nh5 15. Rfd1 Qe7 16. Bf1 Nf4 17. b4 {Black is
doomed to passivity. White should only keep his bishop pair.}) 9. a4 Re8 10.
Qc2 e5 11. dxe5 dxe5 $6 {The c6-knight stands poorly and Black should have
better exhanged it! Now, Black doesn't have good control of the d5-square
after an eventual Nc4-Ne3, because his knight is standing on c6 and there is
no ...c7-c6.} ({Better would have been} 11... Nxe5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 ({In case of} 
12... Rxe5 13. f4 ({Also possible is} 13. Bh4) 13... Rxg5 14. fxg5 Ng4 15. Bc4
{when Black does not have compensation for the exchange.}) 13. Rfd1 Qe7 14. Nc4
Bg4 15. f3 $14) 12. b4 Bd7 13. Rfd1 Qc8 14. Nc4 Bg4 15. Be2 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Qe6
17. Ne3 $16 {White has a huge advantage. Later on, he converted it without any
problems.} Red8 (17... Ne7 18. Qa2 (18. Be2 $16) 18... Qxa2 19. Rxa2 Red8 20.
Rad2 $16) 18. Nd5 (18. Be2 $16) 18... Rbc8 (18... Rd7 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Bg4 $18
) 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Bg4 Qd6 21. Bxc8 Rxc8 22. Nb6 Nxb4 23. Nxc8 Nxc2 24. Nxd6
Nxa1 25. Ne8 (25. Rxa1 cxd6 26. Rb1 b5 27. axb5 axb5 28. c4 bxc4 29. Rc1 Kg7
30. Rxc4 Be7 31. Rc1 Kf6 32. Rd1 Ke6 33. Rd5 f5 34. f3 fxe4 35. fxe4 $18) 25...
Be7 26. Rxa1 1-0

