1. d4 {In this great game, Kasparov shows the typical ideas in the tore with
d6-e5 ....like the plan wth Nc4-Nfd2-f3-Bf2-a4-b4 etc ....it doesn't matter if
white will put his bishop on c4 or d3 or e2, you can always get the same type
of position !} (1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Bg4 5. d3 Nbd7 6. Nbd2 e5
7. h3 Bh5 8. e4 dxe4 9. dxe4 Be7 10. Kh2 O-O 11. b3 Re8 12. Bb2 Qc7 13. Qe2 Bf8
14. Rfe1 b5 $1 15. a3 Nc5 $15 {this is exactly the reversed position (if we
exclude the move Kh2)} 16. Rac1 a5 17. Qe3 Nfd7 18. Nh4 f6 19. Bf3 Bf7 20. Bg4
Ne6 21. Nf5 c5) (1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 {i would like to make my point
of the Torre somewhat resembling the Spanish more clear} 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6.
c3 g6 7. Nbd2 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 b5 10. Bc2 {if we compare this to Torre we
can find some similarities-however in contrast we still have not developed Bc1
here and we need to find a square for Nd2. Otherwise, we would be very happy
to have the Bg5 here. The knight on d2 is actually best placed there and here
it would need to move while in the Torre it wouldn't. Therefore i would say
that in fact, the Torre is a better version of some lines in Spanish.}) 1...
Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bg5 Bg7 4. Nbd2 d6 (4... O-O 5. e4 $6 (5. c3 $1 d6 6. e4 {
white can choose to establish e4 as Black has already lost a tempo for d6 and
switching to a more aggressive approach with d5 is not as strong.}) 5... d5 6.
e5 Ne4 7. Bf4 c5 8. c3 Nc6 9. Bd3 Bf5) 5. e4 {Kasparov was playing a lot of
Torre since 2 of his mentors would employ it rather often - Vassily Smyslov
and Tigran Petrosian. Both of them played it tremendously well and achieved
great results often choosing young tactical players such as nunn} (5. c3 $1 O-O
6. e3 {SOS !! THIS IS ALSO VERY GOOD IF YOU WANT TO COMPLETELY AVOID CONCRETE
THEORY AFTER 6.e4-c5! 7.dc5 etc The idea is to have a more stable position
against c5} c5 (6... Nbd7 7. Bd3 h6 8. Bh4 e5 9. O-O Qe8 10. e4 $1 $14 {
white did lose a tempo but black cannot make use of it as he got a somewhat
bad version of the Torre. The idea behind playing e3 first is to rule out the
plan with c5 which is not so effective anymore}) 7. Be2 Nc6 (7... cxd4 8. exd4
Nc6 9. O-O e5 10. dxe5 dxe5) 8. O-O $14) (5. e3 $1 {this is another very good
way to play the Tore..e3 and Bc4...AVOIDING ALL KINDS OF THEORY...BUT KEEPING
ALL THE TYPICAL PLANS!} O-O 6. Bc4) 5... O-O 6. c3 Nbd7 {again Black has 3
main options here} (6... Nc6 {in my view this is not great for black. ofc
white can choose from all the bishop moves after Nbd7 but now has an
additional idea- playing Bb5 where he intends to capture the knight spoiling
Black's structure!} 7. Bd3 $1 {is also playable. The Nc6 puts direct pressure
on d4 after e5 so white is forced to take} (7. Bb5 $1 Bd7 (7... a6 8. Bxc6 bxc6
9. O-O $14 h6 10. Bh4 {white has a very healthy position, with the better pawn
structure and active pieces! ...don't mind the computer's evaluation which
says it is equal! ..white has the much easier play!}) 8. O-O a6 {now the
bishop goes back with the typical Torre position and the usual ideas taking on
e5, qc2 pushing b4} (8... Qe8 9. a4 (9. Re1 Nxd4) (9. Bd3) 9... a6 10. Bc4) 9.
Be2 e5 10. dxe5 (10. d5 $2 Ne7) 10... dxe5 11. b4 (11. Qc2 h6 12. Bh4) 11...
Re8 12. a4 Qe7 13. Qc2) 7... e5 8. dxe5 $1 {SOS !! WITH HIS KNIGHT ON c6 HE IS
THREATENING TO TAKE ON d4 AND PUT A LOT OF PRESSURE ON THIS PAWN! ...so we
have to take de5! immediately! (but if he had played Nbd7 and e5 or c5, WE
WOULDNT HAVE TO TAKE ..because the knight from d7 does not put pressure on our
centre!} (8. O-O {would give black very active counterplay} exd4 9. cxd4 h6 10.
Bh4 g5 11. Bg3 Nh5 (11... g4)) 8... dxe5 $6 {in fact, this knight on c6 stands
very poorly..and it was better for black to exchange it! Now white will
develop an initiative on the queenside chasing the knight away} (8... Nxe5 {
strategically speaking black should take with the knight-- this position is
very similar to some lines in the Spanish game. White is slightly better} 9.
Nxe5 dxe5 10. Qc2) 9. Qc2 {protecting the bishop and placing the queen on its
most natural square} Re8 10. O-O h6 11. Bh4 Qe7 12. Nc4 $16 (12. b4 $14) (12.
Rfe1) 12... Bg4 13. Nfd2 (13. Be2 {if nfd2 was not working for some reason can
also be played} Rad8 14. Ne3 {is White's best bet-- the knight is eyeing d45
at any moment- the NC6 blocks the way of c6} (14. Rfd1) (14. b4) (14. Rfe1)
14... Be6 15. Bc4 {white exchanges the bishop protecting b5 and achieves a
position with comfortable play--- more space on the queenside, control over d5
and a slightly better bishop} (15. b4) 15... Bxc4 16. Nxc4) 13... Rad8 14. f3
Bc8 15. Rfd1 $14 Qf8 16. Bf1 a6 17. b4) (6... c5 7. dxc5 $1 (7. Be2 $6 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Nc6 9. O-O h6 10. Bh4 g5 11. Bg3 Nh5) 7... dxc5 8. Be2 (8. Bc4 {me to Be2.
..}) (8. a4) 8... Nc6 9. O-O h6 10. Bh4 Nh5 (10... b6 11. Qc2) 11. Qc2 $1 (11.
Re1 $5 Nf4 (11... Qc7 $1 $132) 12. Bf1 Nd3 13. Re3 Nxb2 14. Qc2 $16) 11... Nf4
(11... Qc7 12. Rfd1 Nf4 13. Bf1 (13. Nc4 $5)) 12. Nc4 $3 Nxe2+ 13. Qxe2 b6 14.
Rfd1 Qc7 15. Ne3 $1 $14 e6 (15... Be6 16. Nd5 $1) 16. Rd2 $1) 7. Be2 (7. Bd3 {
SOS !! ALSO VERY GOOD...AND THE MOVE I PREFER THE MOST! ...NOW, AFTER e7-e5,
WITH OUR BISHOP ON d3 WE DONT HAVE TO TAKE IMMEDIATELY de5 , BECAUSE e4 is
well protected!........so..its either 1.Be2-e5 2.de5! or 1.Bc4-e5 2.de5! or 1.
Bd3-e5 2.0-0! wthout taking on e5!} e5 (7... c5 8. O-O $1) 8. O-O h6 9. Bh4 b6
10. Re1 Bb7 11. Qc2 a6 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. b4 Re8 14. Nc4 Qe7 15. a4 Rac8 16. Bf1
$14) (7. Bc4 e5 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. O-O Re8 10. Re1 h6 11. Bh4 c6 12. Qc2 b6 13.
Rad1 Bb7 14. Bf1 (14. Bg3 Nh5 15. b4 Nxg3 16. hxg3 h5) 14... Qc7 (14... g5 15.
Bg3 Nh5 16. Nc4 Nxg3 17. hxg3) 15. Nc4 Bf8 16. Nfd2) 7... e5 8. dxe5 (8. O-O $6
h6 9. Bh4 (9. Be3 $4 Ng4) 9... exd4 10. cxd4 g5 11. Bg3 Re8 12. Bd3 Nh5 13. Nb3
Nxg3 14. hxg3 c5) 8... dxe5 (8... Nxe5 {i would consider this as the better
alternative for black} 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. O-O h6 11. Bh4 {some sample variations
now} (11. Be3) 11... Be6 12. Qc2 Qe7 13. Bc4 (13. Nc4 Qe8 14. a3 Nxe4 15. Qxe4
f5 16. Qc2 g5 17. f4 (17. Bg3 f4 18. Bd3 (18. Nd2) 18... fxg3 19. hxg3)) 13...
Bxc4 14. Nxc4 Qe6 (14... Rfd8 15. b4 (15. Rfd1) (15. f3 $4 Qc5+) 15... c6 (
15... c5 16. b5 (16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. b5)) 16. f3 (16. a4 Qe6 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18.
Qe2) 16... Qe6 17. Ne3 Rd7 18. Rfd1) 15. Ne3 c6 16. f3 Rfd8 17. Rfd1 Kh7 18.
Qb3 Qxb3 19. axb3) 9. O-O b6 10. Re1 Bb7 11. Qc2 h6 12. Bh4 Qe7 (12... g5 {
would be a bad choice} 13. Bg3 Nh5 14. Nc4 Nxg3 15. hxg3 Nc5 16. Nfd2 {some
calculations are required to choose the most suitable move order to achieve
the desired setup} (16. Bf1) (16. Nfxe5 {taking would be bad as white
transforms the nature of the position- from static it suddenly becomes dynamic.
(unless we have a forcing winning line)} Bxe4) 16... Ne6 17. Ne3 {black is
strategically lost}) 13. Bf1 Rfe8 14. b4 a6 (14... c5 {shows a
misunderstanding. White would place Nc4 or in an endgame even have a route for
his king} 15. b5) (14... a5 15. a3 {keeping control on the c5 square} Kh7 (
15... axb4 16. cxb4 (16. axb4) 16... c5 17. b5 {Nc4 to follow and later an
advance of the a-pawn}) 16. Bb5 c6 17. Bf1 b5) 15. Nc4 (15. a4 a5 16. bxa5 Rxa5
17. Nb3 Raa8 18. a5) 15... Rac8 {vlack wants to play c5 and then b5 gaining
the initiative} 16. a4 {preventing any ideas with b5 or c5. In the case of c5
White would be pressing after b5 and fixating the weakness on b6. Additionally,
he can make use of the d6 square} (16. Rad1) 16... Qe6 (16... c5 17. b5 axb5
18. axb5) 17. Nfd2 {protecting e4. only typical moves so far} Nh5 18. f3 $3 {
SOS !! when we have the chance, it's better to keep the Bh4 and not exchange
it on f6....however, even f we take o f6, white keeps some advantage!} (18. Ne3
{is possible too} Bf6 19. Bxf6 Nhxf6 20. f3) (18. Bg3 Nxg3 19. hxg3 h5 (19...
g5)) (18. Rad1 Bf6 19. Bxf6 Qxf6 20. Nb3 (20. Qd3 $5 Rcd8 21. Qe3)) 18... Bf6 (
18... f5 {could be chosen by a player who tries to keep the initiative at any
cost. However, white is more than prepared to face it and as a result, Black's
attempted attack progresses very slowly. In the meantime, white has a strong
play in the centre and the queenside} 19. Bf2 (19. Na5 bxa5 20. Bc4) (19. exf5)
19... f4 20. Nb3 g5 21. Nca5) 19. Bf2 $3 $16 (19. Bxf6 Nhxf6) 19... Bg5 20. Ne3
(20. Ra2) 20... Ndf6 21. c4 {the first move that Kasparov had to make on his
own. Up to this point, he was just playing the simple string moves following
the standard plan of the torre} c6 (21... c5 {now d5 is under white's control}
22. bxc5 (22. b5 a5 23. Nd5 Nd7 (23... Bxd5 24. exd5 Qd7)) 22... bxc5 23. Nd5 {
[%cal Yf6d5,Yc4d5]} Nxd5 24. cxd5 Qe7 25. Nc4) 22. Nb3 Nd7 23. c5 {opening up
the c4 square for his B and N} b5 (23... bxc5 24. bxc5 (24. Nxc5 Nxc5 25. Qxc5)
) 24. Red1 {rook on e1 has done its job to protect e5 at the necessary moment
and now switches to a better position. Note that the Ra1 is perfectly placed} (
24. Na5 Ba8 25. Qc3 Kh7 (25... Nhf6) 26. Bd3 Rcd8 27. Bb1 (27. Bc2)) 24... Be7
25. Nc4 $3 {if black takes white would recapture with the bishop chasing the
queen again and take the knight on d7 ending a pawn up} Rc7 26. Nd6 {and Garry
smoothly converted his advantage.} Rb8 27. axb5 cxb5 28. Nxb7 Rbxb7 29. Qa2 Nb8
30. Na5 Qxa2 31. Rxa2 Ra7 32. c6 Ra8 33. Rc2 Bxb4 34. Rd8+ Kg7 35. Bb6 Bxa5 36.
Bxa5 Rxc6 37. Rxb8 Rxb8 38. Rxc6 b4 39. Bc7 1-0

