1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 g6 4. Nf3 {SUPER SOS ....THIS MOVE ORDER (without a
fast e7-e5) does not force us to play c2-c3, so in this game, GM Kovalenko
shows another very interesting way to continue. His plan is based on a fast
Re1 and e4-e5, with our pawn still on c2. If we play c3, we dont have the time
for that, so we should switch to a Tore setup.} Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. Re1 $1 {
White is immediately preparing the advance e4-e5.} (6. h3 $5 {is also
interesting but you should be careful. This move does not work well with Bg5.
A possible continuation would be} Nbd7 7. c3 e5 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 b6 10. a4 a6
11. b4 Bb7 12. Qb3 {with a slight advantage for White.}) ({If you want to play
in a Torre style, then my suggestion would be} 6. c3 $5 Nbd7 ({By far, we all
know that the position arising after} 6... Nc6 7. Bg5 e5 8. dxe5 Nxe5 (8...
dxe5 9. Qc2 $16) 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Qc2 $14 {is slightly better for White.}) ({
A typical attempt to attack the centre is} 6... c5 {In my opinion, White's
most precise reaction would be} 7. Re1 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bg4 9. Nbd2 $1 {[%cal
Gh2h3] This is the point. White is now ready to recapture on f3 with a knight.}
Nc6 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 e5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 (12... dxe5 13. Bg5 $14) 13. Nxe5
dxe5 14. Be3 {White's bishop pair gives him a slight advantage.}) 7. Bg5 e5 8.
Nbd2 h6 9. Bh4 $14 {White managed to obtain a favourable version of the Torre.}
) 6... c5 7. dxc5 $1 {Another very good way to get a big advantage!} ({More
typical would be} 7. c3 $16 cxd4 8. cxd4 Nc6 ({We already know that} 8... Bg4 {
is best answered by} 9. Nbd2 $1 Nc6 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 $14) 9. h3 $16 {
Preventing ...Bg4 once and for all. The following line is quite possible:} e5
10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Nc3 Be6 12. Bb5 Qc7 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Be3 $16 {White enjoys
a huge advantage.}) 7... dxc5 8. e5 $1 Nd5 ({After} 8... Ng4 9. Bf4 Nc6 10. Na3
b6 11. h3 Nh6 12. Be4 {White's advantage is out of question.}) 9. Be4 Be6 10.
Ng5 $16 {This move is enough for a huge advantage.} ({Even stronger would have
been} 10. Nc3 $3 $18 Nxc3 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Bxb7 Nd7 13. Bxa8 Rxa8 14. bxc3 $18
{when White is winning on the spot.}) 10... Nc6 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. c4 Ndb4 13.
a3 Na6 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Qe2 Qc7 16. Nc3 Rad8 17. f4 Rd4 18. Be3 Rdxf4 19. Bxf4
Rxf4 20. Rad1 Rd4 21. g3 Qd7 22. Kg2 Nc7 23. Ne4 Na6 24. Ng5 Bh6 25. Nf3 Rxd1
26. Rxd1 Qc8 27. h4 Qb7 28. Rd8+ Kg7 29. g4 Bf4 30. Rd3 Nb8 31. g5 Nd7 32. Kh3
Qc7 33. Qe4 Bc1 34. Rb3 Nb6 35. Qe1 Bf4 36. Kg4 Nxc4 37. Kxf4 Qd7 38. Qe4 Nb6
39. Kg3 c4 40. Rc3 Qd1 1-0

