1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. Re1 {This move is
totally pointless when White has Nbd2 at his disposal. As we will see in this
game, Black doesn't have enough resources to put pressure on d4.} Bg4 $2 7.
Nbd2 Nc6 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Nxf3 {Now, Black does not have any compensation for
White's bishop pair.} e5 ({Obviously,} 9... Nb4 {will be met by} 10. Bf1 {
when it's not clear what the b4-knight is doing.}) 10. c3 $5 $16 {This move is
enough for a big advantage.} ({Being fan of static positions, I would have
probably preferred} 10. dxe5 $5 $16 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. c3 $16 {when White
is better.} ({Another possibility is} 12. Bg5 h6 13. Be3 $16 {with the same
type of play.})) 10... exd4 11. cxd4 Nb4 12. Bb1 c5 {When White has the bishop
pair, this type of counterplay does not work quite well.} {After} 13. dxc5 dxc5
14. e5 Nd7 15. Qb3 Qc7 16. e6 $18 {White was already winning.} fxe6 17. Ng5 Bd4
18. Re2 Qd6 19. Qxe6+ Qxe6 20. Nxe6 Rae8 21. a3 Nd5 22. Ba2 N7b6 23. Nxd4 cxd4
24. Kf1 Kg7 25. Bd2 Rxe2 26. Kxe2 Nf4+ 27. Bxf4 Rxf4 28. Rc1 Re4+ 29. Kd3 Re7
30. Rc2 Rd7 31. Be6 Re7 32. Bg4 Nd5 33. Kxd4 Nf4 34. g3 h5 35. gxf4 hxg4 36.
hxg4 Kf6 37. Kd5 Rd7+ 38. Ke4 Re7+ 39. Kf3 Rh7 40. g5+ Ke6 41. Re2+ Kf7 42. f5
gxf5 43. Kf4 Rh3 44. Kxf5 Rf3+ 45. Kg4 Rd3 46. f4 Rd4 47. Kf5 Rd5+ 48. Re5 Rd2
49. g6+ Kf8 50. Kf6 Rxb2 1-0

