{[%evp 0,61,41,30,70,70,64,18,59,53,50,49,59,31,55,40,51,22,63,57,67,9,9,32,28,
12,46,35,100,82,82,78,68,81,79,76,49,58,52,58,90,102,150,151,155,139,160,179,
228,228,336,273,361,355,355,361,337,425,420,304,435,337,793,793]} 1. d4 d6 2.
e4 Nf6 3. Bd3 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. Re1 Nbd7 7. c3 {This is the more
classcial way of handling the position.} ({More ambitious would have been} 7.
e5) 7... c5 8. h3 {This move is usually connected with the idea of developing
the bishop to e3.} ({A Torre type of play will arise after} 8. Bg5 e5 9. dxe5
Nxe5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Qc2 {when White has a huge advantage in view of the
weakening ...c7-c5 move.}) ({When the black pawn is on e7, White can even
consider} 8. d5 $5) ({In my opinion, however, the most ambitious is} 8. e5 $16)
8... cxd4 ({Whenever Black plays} 8... e5 {we shouldn't allow him to take
twice on d4. The best reaction is} 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. a4 b6 11. Na3 Bb7 12. Bg5 {
getting our familiar Torre type of play. Obviously, the inclusion of ...c7-c5
is in White's favour.}) 9. cxd4 e5 10. d5 $6 {This premature decision is
typical for a blitz game. Now, the black knight gets access to the wonderful
c5-square.} ({A very logical continuation would have been} 10. Nc3 $1 $16 a6
11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Bc4 $1 {In this symmetrical position, White
has an obvious advantage in view of the superior activity of his pieces.}) ({
Another sound continuation would have been} 10. dxe5 $1 $16 Nxe5 11. Nc3 $3 Be6
12. Bf4 $16 {with a huge advantage.}) 10... Nc5 11. Nc3 Nxd3 12. Qxd3 a6 13. a4
a5 14. Be3 Bd7 15. Nd2 Ne8 16. Nc4 Ra6 17. Nb5 f5 18. f3 Qh4 19. Nb6 Rf7 20.
Nxd7 Rxd7 21. exf5 Qh5 22. fxg6 hxg6 23. Rac1 Kh7 24. Rc8 Nf6 25. Rec1 Qh4 26.
Nc7 e4 27. fxe4 Nxe4 28. Nxa6 bxa6 29. Rf1 Be5 30. Bd4 Nc5 31. Bxe5 1-0

