1. d4 (1. e4 d6 2. d4) 1... d6 (1... g6 {going for the Modern defence ...but
it will transpose in the end} 2. e4 $1 Bg7 3. Nf3 $1 c6 (3... d6 4. c3 $1 {
transposes}) 4. Bd3 $3 d5 5. exd5 $1 (5. e5 $3 $16 {in fact, this is probably
even stronger than 5.ed5  !!} Bg4 6. Nbd2 c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Nxf3 $16
cxd4 10. cxd4 Qb6 11. O-O e6 12. Be3 $16 (12. b4 $3 $16 {White is almost
winning here..according to the computer!!})) 5... cxd5 6. c3 $1 $14 {with a
very nice version of the exhange caro-can, because we save a tempo..as playing
h2-h3 is not necessary here !} Bg4 $6 7. Nbd2 $1 Nc6 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Nxf3 $16 Nf6
10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 e6 12. Bf4 $16) 2. e4 $1 {No matter if you are an e4 or a
d4 player, when Black answers your first move with 1...d6, the best thing to
do is to .. occupy the center with two pawns!} Nf6 3. Bd3 $1 {This is an
exciting way to avoid all three possible openings by Black after 1...d6  (The
Pirc), The Modern (Pirc without Nf6) and the Philidor! There is a big chance
that your opponent will feel uncomfortable after 3.Bd3! There is a big chance
that he will go wrong sooner or later, because if he tries to repeat the same
ideas with his Pirc or Philidor Defence, surprisingly, they do not work well
after 3.Bd3 and c3 !!} e5 (3... g6 $6 {is not the most accurate reply} 4. Nf3 {
and, sooner or later, Black will have to play e7-e5 himself reaching the same
positions} Bg7 (4... Nbd7 {Is also possible, but White can grab the initiative
after:} 5. e5 Nd5 6. e6 fxe6 7. Ng5 N7f6 8. a3 Bg7 9. c4 $16) 5. O-O O-O 6. Re1
$14 (6. h3 $14) 6... Nc6 7. c3 e5 8. h3 $1 (8. dxe5 $5 {Is also possible} dxe5
9. Qc2 $14 (9. Bg5 {Leads to Torre} h6 10. Bh4 $14) (9. h3 $5 $14 a5 10. a4 Be6
11. Na3 Qe7 12. Bb5 $16 {and White has a slight advantage} (12. Qc2 Rad8 13.
Be3 $16))) 8... a5 9. Be3 $1 (9. Bg5) 9... Re8 10. Nbd2 {White keeps the
tension and has a better position}) 4. c3 (4. dxe5 {Is not very good here, as
I already mentioned in the other lectures, because the bishop is not committed
to g7 yet.} dxe5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. c3) (4. Nf3 {I don't like this setup for White,
but it is playable} exd4 5. Nxd4) 4... Nbd7 $5 {super sos !!! A cunning move
order, because now if we try our regular 5.Nf3 , Black has the interesting
option of 5...d6-d5 !? although again after 5.Qe2!! White is slightly better!
So, if you are not interested in studying the complications after 5.f4!, then
5.Nf3 is your move...for a slight and safe advantage (if Black knows d6-d5! ..
if not the advantage might be bigger!)} (4... Nc6 $6 {not good enough} 5. Nf3
$1 Bg4 (5... g6 6. O-O $1 (6. dxe5 $14 Nxe5 $1 {SOS !!! BLACK SHOULD ALMOST
ALWAYS ANSWER 1.de5 with Nxe5! ...trading a pair of knights!!} 7. Nxe5 dxe5 8.
Qe2 Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. a4 $1 $14 (10. Bg5 $14) 10... a5 11. Na3) 6... Bg7 7. h3
$1 (7. Re1 $1 O-O 8. Bg5 $14) (7. dxe5 Nxe5 8. Nxe5 dxe5 9. a4 $14) (7. Nbd2 $1
O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. dxe5 Nxe5 (9... dxe5 10. Nc4 $16) 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Nf3 $14)
(7. Bg5 $14) 7... O-O 8. Re1 $14 {and the plan might be Be3!! and Nbd2 in Ruy
Lopez Style...or Bg5 in Torre style ( or Na3!! in case of a7-a5 by black!)} Re8
(8... a5 9. Na3 $3 (9. Be3 $3 Re8 10. Nbd2 h6 11. a3 $16 Bd7 12. b3) (9. Bg5
$14) 9... Re8 10. Nb5 $3 $16) (8... h6 9. Be3 $1 Re8 10. Nbd2 Bd7 11. a3 a5 12.
b3 $16) 9. Bc2 $1 (9. Na3 $1 $14) (9. Bg5 $14) 9... exd4 10. cxd4 Nb4 11. Nc3
Nxc2 12. Qxc2 $16 d5 13. e5) (5... Be7 6. d5 $1 (6. O-O O-O 7. h3 $14 exd4 8.
cxd4 Nb4 9. Nc3 Nxd3 10. Qxd3 $14 c6 11. Bf4) 6... Nb8 7. c4 Nbd7 8. Nc3 $16 {
is a perfect version of the old Indian defence!}) 6. d5 Ne7 7. h3 Bd7 8. c4 Ng6
9. Nc3 $16) (4... Be7 $6 {very passive as well..not much to see here...both 5.
Ne2!? , and the simple 5. Nf3! are good enought for an advantage!  THE PROBLEM
IS..THAT BLACK OFTEN GETS CONFUSED AND TRIES TO EMPLOY A  d6-c6-Nbd7-Qc7 and
b5 or b6 set-up ... WHICH WORK WELL IN A REGULAR PHILIDOR WITH Nc3 ....BUT NOT
IN THE ST-UP WITH c3-Bd3-Nbd2 !!! (PAP)} 5. Nf3 $1 (5. Ne2 $1 {also very good
! the idea is pretty simple : ...0-0 and f2-f4! ...with or without h3  !!} O-O
6. O-O Nbd7 (6... c6 7. f4) (6... Nc6 7. f4 exd4 8. Nxd4 $1 $14) (6... a5 7. f4
$16) 7. f4 $1 c5 (7... exf4 8. Bxf4 $16 (8. Nxf4 $16)) 8. h3 $1 $14 (8. Kh1 $14
Re8) 8... Re8 (8... Qc7 9. Be3 b6 10. Ng3 Re8 11. Nd2 $16) 9. fxe5 dxe5 10. d5
Nf8 11. Ng3 $16 Ng6 12. Nd2 Bd7 13. a4 Nf4 14. Nc4) 5... Nbd7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1
$14 c6 (7... Re8 8. Nbd2 Bf8 9. Nf1 g6 10. Ng3 $14 (10. Bg5 Bg7 11. N1d2 $5 $14
)) 8. Nbd2 (8. Bc2 $5 Qc7 9. Nbd2 Rd8 10. Nf1 Nf8 11. Ng3 Ng6 12. h3 $14) 8...
Qc7 9. Nf1 $16 (9. h3 $16)) (4... g6 5. Nf3 Nbd7 6. O-O Bg7 7. Re1 $1 (7. h3
O-O 8. Be3 $14 Re8 9. Nbd2) 7... O-O 8. Bg5 $14 Re8 9. Nbd2 h6 10. Bh4 b6 11.
Qc2 Bb7 12. Rad1 $14) 5. f4 $3 (5. Nf3 $5 {this is good...and most players do
not know 5...d5!? where we are still slightly better...everyone will either
play Be7 or g6-Bg7 ..wth a comfortable += ..or maybe even +/-} d5 $1 (5... Be7
6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c5 8. d5 $14 (8. dxe5 $14)) 6. Qe2 $3 {is the best move for
White. I believe that White is better in all the lines, but the position stays
quite tricky. The position is very rare with just a few games in the database.}
Qe7 (6... dxe4 7. Bxe4 Qe7 (7... Nxe4 8. Qxe4 Bd6 9. dxe5 (9. O-O) 9... Qe7 (
9... Nc5 10. Qd4 $14 Be7 11. O-O {White is a pawn up, but Black has some
compensation}) 10. O-O Nxe5 $2 {is a mistake} (10... f6 11. Re1 fxe5 12. Nbd2 (
12. Bg5 Qf7 13. Nbd2 O-O 14. Bh4 Nc5 15. Qe3 $14) 12... O-O 13. Nc4 Nf6 14. Bg5
$16 {White is slightly better}) 11. Nxe5 O-O (11... Bxe5 12. Re1 f6 (12... Bd6
13. Qa4+) 13. f4 $18 Bd6 14. Qa4+ Bd7 15. Rxe7+ $18) 12. Re1 Re8 13. Bf4 f6 14.
Nd2 fxe5 15. Bg3 $16 Qf7 16. Nf3 Bf5 17. Qxb7 $18) 8. dxe5 Nxe4 (8... Nxe5 $2
9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Bc6+) 9. Qxe4 Nc5 10. Qd4 Bf5 11. O-O $14) 7. Nbd2 $1 exd4 {
Black needs to start liquidating the centre} 8. Nxd4 (8. cxd4 $6 dxe4 9. Nxe4
Nxe4 10. Bxe4 Nf6 11. Bd3 Qxe2+ $15) 8... dxe4 (8... Nc5 9. Bb5+ Bd7 (9... c6
$2 10. Nxc6 $18) 10. e5 Bxb5 11. Nxb5 Nfe4 12. O-O $16 {White has a solid
advantage, but you can investigate it further if you are interested}) 9. Nxe4
Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Nc5 11. Qxe7+ Bxe7 12. Bc4 $14 O-O 13. Bf4 c6 14. O-O-O {White
has more active pieces and despite the symmetry, he is slightly better.}) (5.
Ne2 $5 {is well met by} d5 $5) 5... Be7 (5... c5 6. dxe5 (6. Ne2 cxd4 7. cxd4
$14 exd4 8. Nxd4 Qb6 9. Be3 Qxb2 10. O-O $3 $18 Qxa1 11. Qd2 d5 12. Nc3) 6...
dxe5 7. Na3 $14 (7. Nf3 $14)) (5... exf4 $2 6. Nh3 $3 {I am glad to find this
very elegant move for White} (6. Bxf4 $16 Be7 7. Ne2 O-O 8. O-O b6 9. Ng3 Re8
10. Nf5 Bf8 11. Nd2 $18) 6... Be7 7. Nxf4 O-O 8. O-O c5 9. Be3 (9. Kh1) 9... b5
10. Nd2 $16) (5... exd4 6. cxd4 c5 7. Nf3 $3 $14 (7. d5 c4 8. Bc2 g6 9. Nc3 Bg7
10. Nf3 O-O 11. a4 $1) (7. Ne2 $3 $14) 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4) 6. Ne2 $1 {[%cal
Re2g3]} O-O 7. Ng3 $5 $14 {This is a totally unknown setup} (7. O-O {It
transposes to another position from my analysys after 4...Be7 5.Ne2 (CTRl + f7)
} c6) 7... c5 8. fxe5 dxe5 9. d5 1-0

